$MD$# Should an Intervention Be a Surprise? Surprise vs. Invitational Interventions Explained

*By Matt Brown | Freedom Interventions | July 22, 2026*

If you're planning an intervention for someone you love, you're probably wrestling with one question that keeps you up at night: should an intervention be a surprise, or should we tell them it's coming?

Maybe the surprise approach feels dishonest — one more secret in a family already keeping too many. Or maybe you're terrified that if your loved one knows what's coming, they'll disappear, show up intoxicated, or talk everyone out of it before the meeting starts.

Both instincts are valid. And here's some relief up front: there is no single right answer.

There are two well-established approaches — surprise and invitational — and both work. The real question is which one fits your loved one and your family. Let's walk through it together.

## What Is a Surprise Intervention?

A surprise intervention is a carefully planned meeting that your loved one doesn't know about in advance. The family gathers with a professional interventionist, prepares and rehearses, and then the person is brought into a room where the people who love them are waiting. This approach is often called the Johnson Model, developed by Vernon Johnson in the 1960s, and it's the version most people picture when they hear the word "intervention."

Why would anyone plan a meeting this way? Because addiction protects itself. When someone is deep in active addiction, the part of them that wants to keep using is skilled at avoiding exactly this kind of conversation. Given advance warning, many people will build their defenses, pick off family members one by one, leave town for a few days, or arrive too impaired to participate.

The element of surprise isn't about cornering someone. It's about getting past the wall the addiction has built long enough for your loved one to actually hear you. A well-run surprise intervention is not an ambush or a shaming session — it's structured, rehearsed, and grounded in love.

## What Is an Invitational Intervention?

An invitational intervention is exactly what it sounds like: your loved one is openly invited to a family meeting, sometimes days ahead of time, and they know the topic will be their substance use. Approaches like the ARISE model and systemic family intervention work this way. There are no secrets, no one waiting behind a door.

The invitational approach treats your loved one as a participant rather than a target. From the very first phone call, they're invited into the process. That transparency can preserve trust in relationships where trust is already stretched thin, and it removes the shock and defensiveness that some people feel when they walk into a room they didn't expect.

The obvious worry is: what if they simply refuse to come? Here's what surprises most families — the process moves forward anyway. The family begins changing how they respond to the addiction whether or not their loved one attends the first meeting. When the family stops covering, rescuing, and absorbing consequences, the addiction gets harder to maintain, and most people eventually join the process.

## Which Type of Intervention Works Better?

Both surprise and invitational interventions are effective when they're professionally guided and well prepared. Across models, professionally led interventions get a strong majority of people to accept help — success rates in the 80 to 90 percent range are commonly reported. The better question isn't which model wins on paper. It's which model fits the person you love.

A surprise intervention tends to be the better fit when:

- Your loved one is a flight risk — they've bolted from hard conversations before, or they have the means and history of simply disappearing when pressed.
- The situation is immediately dangerous. With substances like fentanyl in the picture, or recent overdoses, waiting weeks for a slower process may be a risk your family can't afford.
- Your loved one has a long track record of manipulating or dividing family members when they sense pressure coming.

An invitational intervention tends to be the better fit when:

- Trust between your loved one and the family is fragile, and a surprise could confirm their belief that everyone is working against them.
- There's significant trauma or a co-occurring mental health condition, where shock and confrontation could destabilize more than help.
- Your loved one has shown some awareness of the problem — moments of honesty, failed attempts to cut back — and might respond to a respectful, open invitation.

## How Do You Choose the Right Approach for Your Family?

Start by honestly assessing how your loved one has responded to being approached before, because past behavior is the best predictor of how intervention day will go. Then weigh the urgency of the situation and the current state of trust in the family. Those three factors — history, safety, and trust — point most families toward the right model.

A few questions worth sitting with:

- When we've raised the subject before, did they engage, shut down, or leave?
- Is there an immediate safety concern — overdose risk, drinking and driving, dangerous withdrawal — that makes speed matter?
- Is our family united enough to hold a firm, loving line, or do we need help getting on the same page first?

Here's the good news: you don't have to make this decision alone. This is precisely what a professional interventionist assesses in the first conversations with your family. In more than two decades of doing this work, I've found that many interventions blend both approaches — the structure of the Johnson Model with the transparency of invitational work. The model serves the family, not the other way around.

## The Question That Matters More Than Surprise

Whether your loved one knows the meeting is coming matters far less than what the family does before and after it. Every successful intervention — surprise or invitational — rests on the same foundation: a family that gets honest, stops enabling, speaks with one loving voice, and follows through on what they say.

If you're agonizing over the surprise question, take heart. The fact that you're thinking this carefully means you're taking it seriously, and that seriousness is exactly what your loved one needs from you right now. Families come back from this. People get well. The conversation you're afraid to have is very often the one that changes everything.

If you're ready to talk through [which approach is right for your family](/blog/how-to-choose-a-professional-interventionist), call Freedom Interventions at **458-298-8000** or visit FreedomInterventions.com. We'll help you find the path that fits — and walk it with you.

## Frequently Asked Questions About Surprise and Invitational Interventions

### Should an intervention be a surprise?
It depends on your loved one and your situation. Surprise interventions work well for people who are likely to avoid or derail a planned conversation, while invitational interventions work well when preserving trust is critical. A professional interventionist can assess your family and recommend the right fit.

### What is the difference between the Johnson Model and an invitational intervention?
The Johnson Model is a surprise approach: the family prepares privately and the loved one learns about the meeting when it happens. Invitational models like ARISE openly invite the person into the process from the beginning. Both are structured, professionally guided, and effective.

### What if my loved one finds out about a surprise intervention?
It's not ruined. An experienced interventionist plans for this possibility and can adapt on the spot — sometimes shifting to a more open, invitational conversation. The preparation your family has done still holds its value either way.

### Do invitational interventions work if the person refuses to attend?
Yes. The family portion of the process continues whether or not the loved one shows up, and as the family changes how they respond to the addiction, most people eventually engage. Refusing the first meeting is rarely the end of the story.

### Will a surprise intervention damage my relationship with my loved one?
When it's done with love, structure, and professional guidance, lasting damage is rare. Many people in recovery describe their intervention as the moment their life turned. The greater risk to your relationship is usually the addiction continuing unchallenged.

### How do I know which type of intervention is right for my family?
Look at three things: how your loved one has responded to being approached before, how urgent the safety picture is, and how much trust remains in the family. Then talk it through with a [professional interventionist](/blog/how-to-choose-a-professional-interventionist), who can recommend an approach — or a blend of both.
